urchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">With rapid advancements in imaging technology, cardiac computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging are increasingly being used for anatomic evaluation, functional assessment, and pathologic diagnosis of the pulmonary valve and right ventricle. MR imaging is especially helpful in evaluating postoperative pulmonary valve function and grading of pulmonary regurgitation. On the other hand, CT has the advantage of high-resolution isovolumetric whole-chest coverage and is able to depict anatomic detail of the pulmonary valve, perivalvular structures, and pulmonary artery branches.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.341135026">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.341135026">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig1a.jpeg" height="950" width="723" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Intraoperative photographs show an open pulmonary root before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> removal of the valvular leaflets and endocardial dissection. The sinutubular junction (red line); the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue dashed line); the border between the muscular infundibulum and the arterial wall of the pulmonary trunk (⋆); and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line), which correspond to the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction, are seen. No “annulus” is supporting the attachments of the leaflets. ⋆ = intervalvular trigones, <i>CSV</i> = crista supraventricularis, <i>SMT</i> = septomarginal trabeculations, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve. <b>(c)</b> Histologic specimen shows the sinotubular junction (red line; <i>STJ),</i> the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue line; <i>A-VAJ</i>)<i>,</i> and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line; <i>H-VAJ)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig1b.jpeg" height="656" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Intraoperative photographs show an open pulmonary root before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> removal of the valvular leaflets and endocardial dissection. The sinutubular junction (red line); the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue dashed line); the border between the muscular infundibulum and the arterial wall of the pulmonary trunk (⋆); and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line), which correspond to the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction, are seen. No “annulus” is supporting the attachments of the leaflets. ⋆ = intervalvular trigones, <i>CSV</i> = crista supraventricularis, <i>SMT</i> = septomarginal trabeculations, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve. <b>(c)</b> Histologic specimen shows the sinotubular junction (red line; <i>STJ),</i> the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue line; <i>A-VAJ</i>)<i>,</i> and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line; <i>H-VAJ)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig1c.jpeg" height="950" width="852" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Intraoperative photographs show an open pulmonary root before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> removal of the valvular leaflets and endocardial dissection. The sinutubular junction (red line); the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue dashed line); the border between the muscular infundibulum and the arterial wall of the pulmonary trunk (⋆); and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line), which correspond to the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction, are seen. No “annulus” is supporting the attachments of the leaflets. ⋆ = intervalvular trigones, <i>CSV</i> = crista supraventricularis, <i>SMT</i> = septomarginal trabeculations, <i>TV</i> = tricuspid valve. <b>(c)</b> Histologic specimen shows the sinotubular junction (red line; <i>STJ),</i> the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction (blue line; <i>A-VAJ</i>)<i>,</i> and the semilunar attachments of the three arterial valvular leaflets (green line; <i>H-VAJ)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig2a.jpeg" height="780" width="778" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> (<b>a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart, obtained in an attitudinal anatomic position at the level of the thorax, shows the pulmonary valve sinuses posterior <i>(P)</i>, right anterolateral <i>(Ra)</i>, and left anterolateral <i>(La)</i> in relation to the heart. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the pulmonary sinuses anterior <i>(A)</i>, left posterior <i>(Lp)</i>, and right posterior <i>(Rp)</i> in relation to the heart. Depending on their relation to the aorta, the sinuses are left-facing, right-facing, or nonfacing. The same rules may be applied to the aortic valve. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a cadaveric heart shows the pulmonary valve sinuses. <i>A</i> = anterior, <i>L</i> = left sinus, <i>LAD</i> = left anterior descending artery, <i>LCx</i> = left circumflex artery, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus, <i>R</i> = right sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig2b.jpeg" height="780" width="697" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> (<b>a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart, obtained in an attitudinal anatomic position at the level of the thorax, shows the pulmonary valve sinuses posterior <i>(P)</i>, right anterolateral <i>(Ra)</i>, and left anterolateral <i>(La)</i> in relation to the heart. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the pulmonary sinuses anterior <i>(A)</i>, left posterior <i>(Lp)</i>, and right posterior <i>(Rp)</i> in relation to the heart. Depending on their relation to the aorta, the sinuses are left-facing, right-facing, or nonfacing. The same rules may be applied to the aortic valve. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a cadaveric heart shows the pulmonary valve sinuses. <i>A</i> = anterior, <i>L</i> = left sinus, <i>LAD</i> = left anterior descending artery, <i>LCx</i> = left circumflex artery, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus, <i>R</i> = right sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig2c.jpeg" height="691" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> (<b>a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart, obtained in an attitudinal anatomic position at the level of the thorax, shows the pulmonary valve sinuses posterior <i>(P)</i>, right anterolateral <i>(Ra)</i>, and left anterolateral <i>(La)</i> in relation to the heart. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the pulmonary sinuses anterior <i>(A)</i>, left posterior <i>(Lp)</i>, and right posterior <i>(Rp)</i> in relation to the heart. Depending on their relation to the aorta, the sinuses are left-facing, right-facing, or nonfacing. The same rules may be applied to the aortic valve. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of a cadaveric heart shows the pulmonary valve sinuses. <i>A</i> = anterior, <i>L</i> = left sinus, <i>LAD</i> = left anterior descending artery, <i>LCx</i> = left circumflex artery, <i>N</i> = noncoronary sinus, <i>R</i> = right sinus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig3a.jpeg" height="1022" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Pulmonary valve anatomy. Anterior volume-rendered <b>(a)</b>, inlet-outlet (in-out) of the right ventricle <b>(b)</b>, and magnified coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the heart obtained at the level of the RVOT show the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction <i>(A-VAJ;</i> blue line in <b>a</b>; blue arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), the anatomic junction between the muscular infundinulum <i>(m)</i> and the elastic arterial wall and the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction (<i>H-VAJ</i>; green line in <b>a</b>; green arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), which corresponds to the semilunar fibrous attachments of the leaflets to the wall or the “pulmonary annuli,” which is much less sturdy than the aortic annuli. Usually, it is difficult to separate the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction from the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction on three-dimensional (3D) volume-rendered images. The sinutubular junction <i>(STJ</i>; red lines), interannular fibrous trigone (⋆), and right <i>(R)</i> and left <i>(L)</i> anterior annuli are also seen. The commissures between the annuli form peripheral apposition of the leaflets, and the pulmonary valve sits above the ventricular septum and is the most superior cardiac valve, a feature that makes safe resection of the pulmonary valve possible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig3b.jpeg" height="677" width="725" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Pulmonary valve anatomy. Anterior volume-rendered <b>(a)</b>, inlet-outlet (in-out) of the right ventricle <b>(b)</b>, and magnified coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the heart obtained at the level of the RVOT show the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction <i>(A-VAJ;</i> blue line in <b>a</b>; blue arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), the anatomic junction between the muscular infundinulum <i>(m)</i> and the elastic arterial wall and the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction (<i>H-VAJ</i>; green line in <b>a</b>; green arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), which corresponds to the semilunar fibrous attachments of the leaflets to the wall or the “pulmonary annuli,” which is much less sturdy than the aortic annuli. Usually, it is difficult to separate the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction from the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction on three-dimensional (3D) volume-rendered images. The sinutubular junction <i>(STJ</i>; red lines), interannular fibrous trigone (⋆), and right <i>(R)</i> and left <i>(L)</i> anterior annuli are also seen. The commissures between the annuli form peripheral apposition of the leaflets, and the pulmonary valve sits above the ventricular septum and is the most superior cardiac valve, a feature that makes safe resection of the pulmonary valve possible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig3c.jpeg" height="810" width="725" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Pulmonary valve anatomy. Anterior volume-rendered <b>(a)</b>, inlet-outlet (in-out) of the right ventricle <b>(b)</b>, and magnified coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the heart obtained at the level of the RVOT show the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction <i>(A-VAJ;</i> blue line in <b>a</b>; blue arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), the anatomic junction between the muscular infundinulum <i>(m)</i> and the elastic arterial wall and the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction (<i>H-VAJ</i>; green line in <b>a</b>; green arrows in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), which corresponds to the semilunar fibrous attachments of the leaflets to the wall or the “pulmonary annuli,” which is much less sturdy than the aortic annuli. Usually, it is difficult to separate the anatomic ventriculoarterial junction from the hemodynamic ventriculoarterial junction on three-dimensional (3D) volume-rendered images. The sinutubular junction <i>(STJ</i>; red lines), interannular fibrous trigone (⋆), and right <i>(R)</i> and left <i>(L)</i> anterior annuli are also seen. The commissures between the annuli form peripheral apposition of the leaflets, and the pulmonary valve sits above the ventricular septum and is the most superior cardiac valve, a feature that makes safe resection of the pulmonary valve possible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig4.jpeg" height="991" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Illustration shows aortopulmonary trunk arterial anastomotic circulation, which is provided by three arterial anastomotic rings between the proximal right and left coronary arterial systems. The right pulmonary conal branches arise from the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> or aorta, and the left conal branches arise from the left main or proximal left anterior descending <i>(LAD)</i> arteries. The right anterior conal branch exists in almost all individuals, and it may arise from the right aortic sinus in as many as one-half of hearts. The left anterior conal branch exists in most hearts, but the right and left posterior conal branches are uncommon. The retroaortic anastomotic ring <i>(3)</i> is mainly related to the Kugel atrial anastomotic network. <i>1</i> = preconal ring (Vieussens arterial ring), <i>2</i> = retroconal ring, <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LCx</i> = left circumflex artery, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig5.jpeg" height="895" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Severe pulmonary valve stenosis in a patient who underwent pulmonary banding and debanding of a ventricular septal defect. Orthogonal phase-contrast MR angiograms obtained perpendicular to the stenotic segment (yellow line) show severe pulmonary valve stenosis. In general, velocity encoding is begun at 150–200 cm/sec and slowly increased to avoid aliasing. In this case, encoded velocity was 450 cm/sec, regurgitant fraction (RF) was 23%, peak velocity was 4.7 m/sec, and gradient was 88 mm Hg.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig6a.jpeg" height="756" width="815" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the dome-shaped pulmonary valve from the arterial aspect. The fused commissures (yellow arrows) pull the sinutubular junction toward the central circular orifice (red arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dysplastic pulmonary valve stenosis. Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the valve show club-shaped myxomatous thickening (red arrows) limited to the free margin of the leaflets. The proximal part of the leaflets appears intact. The sinuses of Valsalva are well developed, and the sinutubular junction (green arrows in <b>b</b>) is constricted. <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig6b.jpeg" height="756" width="531" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the dome-shaped pulmonary valve from the arterial aspect. The fused commissures (yellow arrows) pull the sinutubular junction toward the central circular orifice (red arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dysplastic pulmonary valve stenosis. Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the valve show club-shaped myxomatous thickening (red arrows) limited to the free margin of the leaflets. The proximal part of the leaflets appears intact. The sinuses of Valsalva are well developed, and the sinutubular junction (green arrows in <b>b</b>) is constricted. <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig6c.jpeg" height="756" width="503" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> <b>(a)</b> Photograph shows the dome-shaped pulmonary valve from the arterial aspect. The fused commissures (yellow arrows) pull the sinutubular junction toward the central circular orifice (red arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dysplastic pulmonary valve stenosis. Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the valve show club-shaped myxomatous thickening (red arrows) limited to the free margin of the leaflets. The proximal part of the leaflets appears intact. The sinuses of Valsalva are well developed, and the sinutubular junction (green arrows in <b>b</b>) is constricted. <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig7a.jpeg" height="893" width="862" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Pulmonary stenosis in a 19-year-old man with LEOPARD syndrome. Volume-rendered <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> CT images of the RVOT show mild thickening of the valve leaflets, narrowing at the sinutubular junction (red arrow), dilated coronary arteries (green arrow in <b>b</b>), poststenotic dilatation of the pulmonary arteries, and a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig7b.jpeg" height="893" width="813" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Pulmonary stenosis in a 19-year-old man with LEOPARD syndrome. Volume-rendered <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> CT images of the RVOT show mild thickening of the valve leaflets, narrowing at the sinutubular junction (red arrow), dilated coronary arteries (green arrow in <b>b</b>), poststenotic dilatation of the pulmonary arteries, and a dilated right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LPA</i> = left pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig8a.jpeg" height="760" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Bi- and quadricuspid pulmonary valves. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and long-axis <b>(b)</b> MR images show a stenotic bicuspid pulmonary valve (arrow in <b>a</b>), flow jet (arrows in <b>b</b>), and poststenotic dilatation of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>. At phase velocity mapping, systolic flow turbulence and increased peak velocity of 3.5 m/sec were seen, with a regurgitant fraction of 35%. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and anterior volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images show a quadricuspid valve with pulmonary stenosis. One extra rudimentary cusp is seen between the posterior and left anterior cusps (arrow in <b>c</b>), the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> appears aneurysmal, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> is hypertrophied.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig8b.jpeg" height="760" width="780" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Bi- and quadricuspid pulmonary valves. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and long-axis <b>(b)</b> MR images show a stenotic bicuspid pulmonary valve (arrow in <b>a</b>), flow jet (arrows in <b>b</b>), and poststenotic dilatation of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>. At phase velocity mapping, systolic flow turbulence and increased peak velocity of 3.5 m/sec were seen, with a regurgitant fraction of 35%. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and anterior volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images show a quadricuspid valve with pulmonary stenosis. One extra rudimentary cusp is seen between the posterior and left anterior cusps (arrow in <b>c</b>), the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> appears aneurysmal, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> is hypertrophied.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig8c.jpeg" height="979" width="896" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Bi- and quadricuspid pulmonary valves. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and long-axis <b>(b)</b> MR images show a stenotic bicuspid pulmonary valve (arrow in <b>a</b>), flow jet (arrows in <b>b</b>), and poststenotic dilatation of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>. At phase velocity mapping, systolic flow turbulence and increased peak velocity of 3.5 m/sec were seen, with a regurgitant fraction of 35%. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and anterior volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images show a quadricuspid valve with pulmonary stenosis. One extra rudimentary cusp is seen between the posterior and left anterior cusps (arrow in <b>c</b>), the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> appears aneurysmal, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> is hypertrophied.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig8d.jpeg" height="979" width="779" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> Bi- and quadricuspid pulmonary valves. <b>(a, b)</b> Transaxial <b>(a)</b> and long-axis <b>(b)</b> MR images show a stenotic bicuspid pulmonary valve (arrow in <b>a</b>), flow jet (arrows in <b>b</b>), and poststenotic dilatation of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>. At phase velocity mapping, systolic flow turbulence and increased peak velocity of 3.5 m/sec were seen, with a regurgitant fraction of 35%. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>RVOT</i> = right ventricular outflow tract. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and anterior volume-rendered <b>(d)</b> CT images show a quadricuspid valve with pulmonary stenosis. One extra rudimentary cusp is seen between the posterior and left anterior cusps (arrow in <b>c</b>), the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> appears aneurysmal, and the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> is hypertrophied.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig9a.jpeg" height="644" width="801" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Subvalvular dynamic stenosis secondary to chronic pulmonary valve stenosis. MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b>, early systole <b>(b)</b>, and late systole <b>(c)</b> show markedly thickened RVOT muscles (red arrows), with a flow jet (green arrows) through the RVOT, a finding best seen in late systole. Subvalvular dynamic obstruction is characterized by a late-peaking jet similar to that of dynamic left ventricular outflow obstruction at MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig9b.jpeg" height="632" width="810" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Subvalvular dynamic stenosis secondary to chronic pulmonary valve stenosis. MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b>, early systole <b>(b)</b>, and late systole <b>(c)</b> show markedly thickened RVOT muscles (red arrows), with a flow jet (green arrows) through the RVOT, a finding best seen in late systole. Subvalvular dynamic obstruction is characterized by a late-peaking jet similar to that of dynamic left ventricular outflow obstruction at MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig9c.jpeg" height="632" width="765" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Subvalvular dynamic stenosis secondary to chronic pulmonary valve stenosis. MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b>, early systole <b>(b)</b>, and late systole <b>(c)</b> show markedly thickened RVOT muscles (red arrows), with a flow jet (green arrows) through the RVOT, a finding best seen in late systole. Subvalvular dynamic obstruction is characterized by a late-peaking jet similar to that of dynamic left ventricular outflow obstruction at MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig10a.jpeg" height="929" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Pulmonary atresia in a 48-year-old patient with a history of TOF. Sagittal <b>(a)</b>, axial <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal volume-rendered color-coded <b>(c)</b> CT images show a long branching conduit (blue area in <b>c</b>) extending between the RVOT and the left pulmonary artery and connected to the left pulmonary artery branches (pink areas in <b>c</b>), with three separate grafts (numbers 1–3). The right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> are markedly dilated, the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> is enlarged, and the pulmonary valve conduit is in close approximation to the sternum (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig10b.jpeg" height="880" width="728" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Pulmonary atresia in a 48-year-old patient with a history of TOF. Sagittal <b>(a)</b>, axial <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal volume-rendered color-coded <b>(c)</b> CT images show a long branching conduit (blue area in <b>c</b>) extending between the RVOT and the left pulmonary artery and connected to the left pulmonary artery branches (pink areas in <b>c</b>), with three separate grafts (numbers 1–3). The right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> are markedly dilated, the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> is enlarged, and the pulmonary valve conduit is in close approximation to the sternum (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig10c.jpeg" height="880" width="747" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Pulmonary atresia in a 48-year-old patient with a history of TOF. Sagittal <b>(a)</b>, axial <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal volume-rendered color-coded <b>(c)</b> CT images show a long branching conduit (blue area in <b>c</b>) extending between the RVOT and the left pulmonary artery and connected to the left pulmonary artery branches (pink areas in <b>c</b>), with three separate grafts (numbers 1–3). The right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> are markedly dilated, the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> is enlarged, and the pulmonary valve conduit is in close approximation to the sternum (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig11a.jpeg" height="907" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> TOF after repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image obtained with an in-plane phase-contrast sequence <b>(b)</b> show severe regurgitant flow at the level of the pulmonary valve (arrows in <b>b</b>), a finding that is better seen on in-phase images. Yellow line = through-plane phase-contrast level. <b>(c)</b> Time-flow curve obtained with through-plane phase-contrast shows systolic forward flow traced in a negative direction and mild late diastolic forward flow, a result of forced atrial contraction and related to impaired relaxation of the right ventricle, with a regurgitant fraction of 46% and peak velocity of 2.1 m/sec. These findings are indicative of moderate to severe pulmonary valve insufficiency.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig11b.jpeg" height="907" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> TOF after repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image obtained with an in-plane phase-contrast sequence <b>(b)</b> show severe regurgitant flow at the level of the pulmonary valve (arrows in <b>b</b>), a finding that is better seen on in-phase images. Yellow line = through-plane phase-contrast level. <b>(c)</b> Time-flow curve obtained with through-plane phase-contrast shows systolic forward flow traced in a negative direction and mild late diastolic forward flow, a result of forced atrial contraction and related to impaired relaxation of the right ventricle, with a regurgitant fraction of 46% and peak velocity of 2.1 m/sec. These findings are indicative of moderate to severe pulmonary valve insufficiency.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig11c.jpeg" height="705" width="1050" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> TOF after repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal oblique cine SSFP MR image obtained with an in-plane phase-contrast sequence <b>(b)</b> show severe regurgitant flow at the level of the pulmonary valve (arrows in <b>b</b>), a finding that is better seen on in-phase images. Yellow line = through-plane phase-contrast level. <b>(c)</b> Time-flow curve obtained with through-plane phase-contrast shows systolic forward flow traced in a negative direction and mild late diastolic forward flow, a result of forced atrial contraction and related to impaired relaxation of the right ventricle, with a regurgitant fraction of 46% and peak velocity of 2.1 m/sec. These findings are indicative of moderate to severe pulmonary valve insufficiency.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig12a.jpeg" height="893" width="752" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Pulmonary valve aneurysm of the sinus of Valsalva and paravalvular fistula. Findings were difficult to show with echocardiography even in retrospect. CT images obtained with volume rendering <b>(a)</b> and at the level of the RVOT <b>(b)</b> clearly show an aneurysm (green arrows) in the medial aspect of the pulmonary valve <i>(PV)</i> straddling the valve leaflet (yellow arrow in <b>b</b>). Two orifices (red arrows in <b>b</b>) are seen (one above the valve and the other below) and are the cause of a paravalvular fistula and regurgitation. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery. These findings are indicative of pulmonary valve aneurysm of the sinus of Valsalva and paravalvular fistula, sequelae of Behçet arteritis, which is possibly a result of aseptic endocarditis, and are difficult to see at echocardiography, even in retrospect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig12b.jpeg" height="893" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Pulmonary valve aneurysm of the sinus of Valsalva and paravalvular fistula. Findings were difficult to show with echocardiography even in retrospect. CT images obtained with volume rendering <b>(a)</b> and at the level of the RVOT <b>(b)</b> clearly show an aneurysm (green arrows) in the medial aspect of the pulmonary valve <i>(PV)</i> straddling the valve leaflet (yellow arrow in <b>b</b>). Two orifices (red arrows in <b>b</b>) are seen (one above the valve and the other below) and are the cause of a paravalvular fistula and regurgitation. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>MPA</i> = main pulmonary artery. These findings are indicative of pulmonary valve aneurysm of the sinus of Valsalva and paravalvular fistula, sequelae of Behçet arteritis, which is possibly a result of aseptic endocarditis, and are difficult to see at echocardiography, even in retrospect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig13a.jpeg" height="940" width="803" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> TOF and anterior paravalvular leak in a patient with an artificial pulmonary valve who underwent stented bioprosthetic valve replacement. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the RVOT <b>(a)</b> and axial MR angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular leak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the struts of a bioprosthetic valve, the cause of artifacts that compromised a full evaluation of the pulmonary valve. Substantial branch pulmonary artery stenosis was treated with balloon dilation and endoluminal stent placement before valve replacement. <b>(c, d)</b> Systolic magnitude <b>(c)</b> and diastolic <b>(d)</b> phase-contrast MR images obtained at the level of the pulmonary valve show the measured regurgitant fraction from the perivalvular insufficiency (arrow), which was approximately 15%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig13b.jpeg" height="940" width="872" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> TOF and anterior paravalvular leak in a patient with an artificial pulmonary valve who underwent stented bioprosthetic valve replacement. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the RVOT <b>(a)</b> and axial MR angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular leak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the struts of a bioprosthetic valve, the cause of artifacts that compromised a full evaluation of the pulmonary valve. Substantial branch pulmonary artery stenosis was treated with balloon dilation and endoluminal stent placement before valve replacement. <b>(c, d)</b> Systolic magnitude <b>(c)</b> and diastolic <b>(d)</b> phase-contrast MR images obtained at the level of the pulmonary valve show the measured regurgitant fraction from the perivalvular insufficiency (arrow), which was approximately 15%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig13c.jpeg" height="845" width="803" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> TOF and anterior paravalvular leak in a patient with an artificial pulmonary valve who underwent stented bioprosthetic valve replacement. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the RVOT <b>(a)</b> and axial MR angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular leak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the struts of a bioprosthetic valve, the cause of artifacts that compromised a full evaluation of the pulmonary valve. Substantial branch pulmonary artery stenosis was treated with balloon dilation and endoluminal stent placement before valve replacement. <b>(c, d)</b> Systolic magnitude <b>(c)</b> and diastolic <b>(d)</b> phase-contrast MR images obtained at the level of the pulmonary valve show the measured regurgitant fraction from the perivalvular insufficiency (arrow), which was approximately 15%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig13d.jpeg" height="845" width="872" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> TOF and anterior paravalvular leak in a patient with an artificial pulmonary valve who underwent stented bioprosthetic valve replacement. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the RVOT <b>(a)</b> and axial MR angiogram <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular leak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and the struts of a bioprosthetic valve, the cause of artifacts that compromised a full evaluation of the pulmonary valve. Substantial branch pulmonary artery stenosis was treated with balloon dilation and endoluminal stent placement before valve replacement. <b>(c, d)</b> Systolic magnitude <b>(c)</b> and diastolic <b>(d)</b> phase-contrast MR images obtained at the level of the pulmonary valve show the measured regurgitant fraction from the perivalvular insufficiency (arrow), which was approximately 15%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig14.jpeg" height="854" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Time-flow curves, phase-contrast magnitude views, and volume-rendered MR angiograms of the pulmonary arteries obtained in a patient who underwent TOF repair show that the right pulmonary artery <i>(RPA)</i> is larger than the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPA)</i>. Chart shows the forward flow <i>(FF)</i>, backward flow <i>(BF)</i>, net flow <i>(net)</i>, and differential regurgitant fraction <i>(RF)</i> of the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i>, RPA, and LPA. Despite the larger size of the RPA, the net flow to the RPA and LPA is equal, a result of the larger RF of the RPA. The elevated RF of the RPA may be related to elevated right-sided pulmonary vascular resistance. At MR imaging of pulmonary regurgitation, both regurgitant volume and fraction values are important and should be reported.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig15a.jpeg" height="819" width="621" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> RVOT in three patients with repaired TOF. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal MR image shows a repaired TOF with an aneurysmal (pyramidal) shape, the most common type. This patient is not a good candidate for transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement. The morphologic characteristics and diameter (arrows) of the RVOT are important criteria for determining suitability for percutaneous valve replacement, given the limited size (usually 14–22 mm) of the synthetic valve. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal MR images show repaired TOFs with a cylindrical outflow tract and a constant diameter. These patients appear to be good candidates for transcatheter valve replacement. Note the stenotic area (red arrows) in <b>c</b>, which should be corrected with balloon angioplasty or stent placement before valve replacement is performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig15b.jpeg" height="819" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> RVOT in three patients with repaired TOF. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal MR image shows a repaired TOF with an aneurysmal (pyramidal) shape, the most common type. This patient is not a good candidate for transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement. The morphologic characteristics and diameter (arrows) of the RVOT are important criteria for determining suitability for percutaneous valve replacement, given the limited size (usually 14–22 mm) of the synthetic valve. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal MR images show repaired TOFs with a cylindrical outflow tract and a constant diameter. These patients appear to be good candidates for transcatheter valve replacement. Note the stenotic area (red arrows) in <b>c</b>, which should be corrected with balloon angioplasty or stent placement before valve replacement is performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig15c.jpeg" height="819" width="615" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> RVOT in three patients with repaired TOF. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal MR image shows a repaired TOF with an aneurysmal (pyramidal) shape, the most common type. This patient is not a good candidate for transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement. The morphologic characteristics and diameter (arrows) of the RVOT are important criteria for determining suitability for percutaneous valve replacement, given the limited size (usually 14–22 mm) of the synthetic valve. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal MR images show repaired TOFs with a cylindrical outflow tract and a constant diameter. These patients appear to be good candidates for transcatheter valve replacement. Note the stenotic area (red arrows) in <b>c</b>, which should be corrected with balloon angioplasty or stent placement before valve replacement is performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig16a.jpeg" height="736" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> 0.5-mm cardiac CT images and sagittal thick-slab maximum intensity projection cardiac CT image <b>(c)</b> obtained after transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement show the stented valve. The leaflets of the stented valve are clearly seen in <b>a</b>. No stent fracture or pseudoaneurysm is seen. Detailed measurements of the valve and stent diameters may be made at CT to evaluate circularity and eccentricity of the stent-valve complex. CT may also be used to evaluate for other complications such as paravalvular leak and to guide transcatheter treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig16b.jpeg" height="696" width="770" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> 0.5-mm cardiac CT images and sagittal thick-slab maximum intensity projection cardiac CT image <b>(c)</b> obtained after transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement show the stented valve. The leaflets of the stented valve are clearly seen in <b>a</b>. No stent fracture or pseudoaneurysm is seen. Detailed measurements of the valve and stent diameters may be made at CT to evaluate circularity and eccentricity of the stent-valve complex. CT may also be used to evaluate for other complications such as paravalvular leak and to guide transcatheter treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig16c.jpeg" height="696" width="805" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> 0.5-mm cardiac CT images and sagittal thick-slab maximum intensity projection cardiac CT image <b>(c)</b> obtained after transcatheter pulmonary valve replacement show the stented valve. The leaflets of the stented valve are clearly seen in <b>a</b>. No stent fracture or pseudoaneurysm is seen. Detailed measurements of the valve and stent diameters may be made at CT to evaluate circularity and eccentricity of the stent-valve complex. CT may also be used to evaluate for other complications such as paravalvular leak and to guide transcatheter treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig17a.jpeg" height="860" width="821" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Ross procedure and pulmonic homografting revision in a 26-year-old man. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> SSFP cine cardiac MR images show a dilated aortic root (pulmonary autograft) and moderate to severe aortic regurgitation, with a regurgitant fraction of 45%.The bioprosthetic pulmonary valve <i>(PV)</i> demonstrated mild stenosis and regurgitation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig17b.jpeg" height="860" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Ross procedure and pulmonic homografting revision in a 26-year-old man. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> SSFP cine cardiac MR images show a dilated aortic root (pulmonary autograft) and moderate to severe aortic regurgitation, with a regurgitant fraction of 45%.The bioprosthetic pulmonary valve <i>(PV)</i> demonstrated mild stenosis and regurgitation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig18a.jpeg" height="837" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Pulmonary artery intimal sarcoma in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows an intraluminal lobulated mass involving the pulmonary valve and main pulmonary artery. Early follow-up images obtained after chemotherapy showed involution of the tumor. <b>(b)</b> Positron emission tomographic/CT image obtained 6 months later shows no significant activity at the site of the primary tumor. However, a recurrent mass is seen in the left pulmonary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.341135026/asset/images/large/rg.341135026.fig18b.jpeg" height="837" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Pulmonary artery intimal sarcoma in a 43-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image shows an intraluminal lobulated mass involving the pulmonary valve and main pulmonary artery. Early follow-up images obtained after chemotherapy showed involution of the tumor. <b>(b)</b> Positron emission tomographic/CT image obtained 6 months later shows no significant activity at the site of the primary tumor. However, a recurrent mass is seen in the left pulmonary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.341135026&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="bib1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Waldo KL, Hutson MR, Ward CC, et al. Secondary heart field contributes myocardium and smooth muscle to the arterial pole of the developing heart. <em>Dev Biol</em> 2005;281(1):78–90.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ydbio.2005.02.012">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15848390/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Secondary+heart+field+contributes+myocardium+and+smooth+muscle+to+the+arterial+pole+of+the+developing+heart&amp;author=KL+Waldo&amp;author=MR+Hutson&amp;author=CC+Ward&amp;publication_year=2005&amp;journal=Dev+Biol&amp;pages=78-90&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.ydbio.2005.02.012&amp;pmid=15848390">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="bib2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Webb S, Qayyum SR, Anderson RH, Lamers WH, Richardson MK. Septation and separation within the outflow tract of the developing heart. <em>J Anat</em> 2003;202(4):327–342.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1469-7580.2003.00168.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12739611/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Septation+and+separation+within+the+outflow+tract+of